        "title": "More of Isaiah's Prophecies Against Nations",
        "introduction": "With the death of Ahaz, Judah has a final opportunity for spiritual renewal. Hezekiah will do what he can do revive Judah, but Isaiah already knows the ultimate outcome and continues to prophesy against the nations who either have brought, or will bring, suffering to God's people. Babylonia in particular is singled out because it is the nation which will carry Judah away into captivity in just a few years. The king of Babylon has the dubious distinction of sharing in Isaiah's oblique references to Satan, the one who has fallen from heaven. Isaiah predicts that Babylon itself will be conquered by the Medo-Persian empire, a fact to which history will later attest. And because they have for years been a threat to Israel, the Philistines are also judged."
